      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_UVA_000055271_page01.jpg"/>
            <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
            <opener>
               <salute>
               My dear Sir
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>
               I have been horribly ungrateful<lb/>
               and ill-bred - but then I have<lb/>
               been ill and a cripple confined<lb/>
               to my bed - I fell from a ladder<lb/>
               upon which at my time of day<lb/>
               I had no business to mount<lb/>
               &amp; cut and bruised my leg so<lb/>
               that I have been not even al<lb/>
               lowed for some time the use<lb/>
               of my hands as I was compelled<lb/>
               to lie flat - It was while<lb/>
               I was in this condition that I<lb/>
               received your most kind &amp;<lb/>
               valuable present - all the <choice>
                  <orig>pre-<lb/>
               cautions</orig>
                  <reg>precautions</reg>
               </choice> you took to ensure<lb/>
               its reaching me safely &amp; free<lb/>
               perfectly succeeded and I <hi rend="underline">was</hi>
               <lb/>
               and am much flattered by<lb/>
               your attention and obliged by your<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_UVA_000055271_page02.jpg"/>
               Memorial of Kindness from the<lb/>
               Author - I like the <title ref="./Workography.xml#Athen1">Athenian<lb/>
               Capture</title> very much - and<lb/>
               hope you will keep the copyright<lb/>
               to yourself.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I am particularly obliged<lb/>
               by your intention to introduce<lb/>
               my name by hook or by crook<lb/>
               among your grateful <choice>
                  <orig>corres<lb/>
               pondents</orig>
                  <reg>correspondents</reg>
               </choice> - and I am sure<lb/>
               that whatever way you do it<lb/>
               will be best and therefore I beg<lb/>
               you to say what you please, of<lb/>
               me and for me -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I should observe however<lb/>
               as to the exact truth of the matter<lb/>
               that I have some little scrap of<lb/>
               interest in copy copyright as I have not<lb/>
               sold that of <title ref="./Workography.xml#Helen1">Helen</title> - but I have given<lb/>
               leave to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BentR1">Bentley</persName> to print a stereotype<lb/>
               Ed<hi rend="superscript">n</hi>. &amp; I think that comes pretty<lb/>
               nearly to the same thing - I only<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_UVA_000055271_page03.jpg"/>   
               mention this for accuracy's sake<lb/>
               - that you may if you think it<lb/>
               worth while frame your sentence<lb/>
               so as to assert that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Miss E</persName> has<lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">little or no</hi> personal interest<lb/>
               in the matter -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
                  I am so shamefully ignorant as<lb/>
                  to my own business concerning<lb/>
                  copyright (which was always<lb/>
                  managed for me by <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">my father</persName> while<lb/>
                  he lived) that I have at last resolved<lb/>
                  to write to my old publisher poor<lb/>
               <persName>Hunter Johnsons</persName> nephew to ask<lb/>
                  him to inform me how the<lb/>
                  matter stands as far as he can<lb/>
                  recollect or find out by his papers<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               The inclosed letter, which I<lb/>
               take the liberty to beg you will<lb/>
               have put with the 2<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> post for me<lb/>
               is to ask these questions &amp; if I<lb/>
               find that any good comes of them<lb/>
               for<lb/>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_UVA_000055271_page04.jpg"/>     
               me I shall presume so far upon<lb/>
               your kind interest as to let<lb/>
               you know of it -<lb/>
               Still with disinterested thanks<lb/>
               &amp; pure admiration of your<lb/>
               eloquent exertions for the<lb/>
               literary British Community<lb/>
               and in truth for the whole world<lb/>
               of literature I am <lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
               <!--include linebreaks, if used. example: <closer> Yours<lb/> Very sincerely<lb/> -->
               Dear Sir<lb/>
               Yours gratefully<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
            <postscript>
               <p><!--A postscript goes here, outside the <closer>. -->
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <placeName>Vicarage Town</placeName>
                  </hi>
                  <lb/>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ButlR1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Butler</persName>, my brother in law,<lb/>
                  from whose house I write<lb/>
                  was a school fellow of<lb/>
                  yours at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Reading_ENK">Reading</placeName> and<lb/>
                  hopes (&amp; so do I) that you<lb/>
                  remember him - He is<lb/>
                  naturally proud of you<lb/>
               </p>
            </postscript>
            <!--You can include a <pb/> here, or inside the postScript.-->
